<subSubSection pageId="106" pageNumber="107" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="106.[151,1436,687,1144]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,724,749]" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Notes.</emphasis>
A single female specimen was collected adjacent to a railway line in 2013. After repeated attempts to recollect the species at the same locality, an additional female and male were found in 2014. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1808" box="[1220,1436,759,784]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis box="[1220,1436,759,784]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Megachile apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
prefers 
<taxonomicName box="[236,353,797,820]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[236,353,797,820]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Centaurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[368,494,796,820]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Muller &amp; Bansac" box="[517,780,796,821]" firstAuthor="Muller" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="329 - 337" refId="ref96975" refString="Muller, A. &amp; Bansac, N. (2004) A specialized pollen-harvesting device in western palaearctic bees of the genus Megachile (Hymenoptera, Apoidea, Megachilidae). Apidologie, 35, 329 - 337. https: // doi. org / 10.1051 / apido: 2004020" type="journal article" year="2004">MÃ¼ller &amp; Bansac 2004</bibRefCitation>
), which was abundant at the collection site. The female of the species is similar to the alfalfa leafcutter bee, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hobbs" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[704,849,831,856]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundata">
<emphasis box="[704,727,833,856]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[740,849,831,856]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">rotundata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the apical projection of the clypeus and the darker scopal hairs on S 
<quantity box="[657,703,868,893]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
addition to S5 (
<bibRefCitation author="Parker" box="[889,1032,868,893]" firstAuthor="Parker" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="61 - 64" refId="ref98568" refString="Parker, F. D. (1978) An illustrated key to alfalfa leafcutter bees Eutricharaea. The Pan-Pacific Entomologist, 54, 61 - 64." type="journal article" year="1978">Parker 1978</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sheffield" box="[1046,1297,868,893]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Sheffield" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="1 - 107" refId="ref102517" refString="Sheffield, C. S., Ratti, C., Packer, L. &amp; Griswold, T. (2011 b) Leafcutter and mason bees of the genus Megachile Latreille (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae) in Canada and Alaska. Canadian Journal of Arthropod Identification, 18, 1 - 107. https: // doi. org / 10.3752 / cjai. 2011.18" type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">
<collectingRegion box="[1046,1148,868,893]" country="United Kingdom" name="Sheffield" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Sheffield</collectingRegion>
<emphasis box="[1156,1215,868,893]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">et al.</emphasis>
2011b
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hobbs" baseAuthorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rotundata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Megachile rotundata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commonly observed in the same area. A continuing expansion of its range is likely, similar to that seen in other cavity nesting megachilid bees (
<bibRefCitation author="Gibbs &amp; Sheffield" box="[606,879,940,965]" firstAuthor="Gibbs" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="21 - 29" refId="ref89103" refString="Gibbs, J. &amp; Sheffield, C. S. (2009) Rapid range expansion of the wool-carder bee, Anthidium manicatum (Linnaeus) (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae), in North America. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 82, 21 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.2317 / jkes 805.27.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Gibbs &amp; 
<collectingRegion box="[711,813,940,965]" country="United Kingdom" name="Sheffield" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Sheffield</collectingRegion>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hinojosa-Diaz" box="[891,1123,940,965]" firstAuthor="Hinojosa-Diaz" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="67 - 71" refId="ref90288" refString="Hinojosa-Diaz, I. (2008) The giant resin bee making its way west: First record in Kansas (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae). ZooKeys, 1, 67 - 71. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 1.17" type="journal article" year="2008">Hinojosa-DÃ­az 2008</bibRefCitation>
). In other 
<collectingCountry box="[1237,1273,940,964]" name="United States of America" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">US</collectingCountry>
localities, this species can be very abundant and aggressively competes for nesting sites (
<bibRefCitation author="Barthell &amp; Thorp" box="[996,1261,975,1000]" firstAuthor="Barthell" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="117 - 124" refId="ref82875" refString="Barthell, J. F. &amp; Thorp, R. W. (1995) Nest usurpation among females of an introduced leaf-cutter bee, Megachile apicalis. Southwestern Entomologist, 20, 117 - 124." type="journal article" year="1995">Barthell &amp; Thorp 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Stephen" box="[1274,1431,975,1000]" firstAuthor="Stephen" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="41 - 66" refId="ref103585" refString="Stephen, W. P. (2003) Solitary bees in North American agriculture: A perspective. In: Strickler, K. &amp; Cane, J. H. (Eds.), For Nonnative Crops, Whence Pollinators of the Future? Entomological Society of America, Lanham, Maryland, pp. 41 - 66." type="book chapter" year="2003">Stephen 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thorp" box="[151,290,1012,1037]" firstAuthor="Thorp" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="143 - 151" refId="ref104219" refString="Thorp, R. W. (1996) Resource overlap among native and introduced bees in California. In: Matheson, A., Buchmann, S. L., O'Toole, C., Westrich, P. &amp; Williams, I. H. (Eds.), The Conservation of Bees. Academic Press Inc., San Diego, California, pp. 143 - 151." type="book chapter" year="1996">Thorp 1996</bibRefCitation>
). Further range extensions of this species might be facilitated by the spread of the invasive plant 
<taxonomicName box="[151,347,1047,1072]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Centaurea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stoebe">
<emphasis box="[151,347,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Centaurea stoebe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (Spotted Knapweed) (
<bibRefCitation author="Richardson" box="[630,890,1047,1072]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Richardson" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="65 - 93" refId="ref100580" refString="Richardson, D. M., Allsopp, N., D'Antonio, C. M., Milton, S. J. &amp; Rejmanek, M. (2000) Plant invasions - the role of mutualisms. Biological Reviews, 75, 65 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 185 x. 1999. tb 00041. x" type="journal article" year="2000">
Richardson 
<emphasis box="[766,823,1047,1072]" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">et al.</emphasis>
2000
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
